aa(lp73
VNow, we send satellites to different orbits
p74
aVdepending on what they're needed for.
p75
aVOne of the most common places we send satellites
p76
aVis the low Earth orbit,
p77
aVpossibly to image the surface of Earth
p78
aVat up to about 2,000 kilometers altitude.
p79
aVSatellites there are naturally buffeted by Earth's atmosphere,
p80
aVso their orbits naturally decay,
p81
aVand they'll eventually burn up,
p82
aVprobably within a couple of decades.
p83
aVAnother common place we send satellites
p84
aVis the geostationary orbit
p85
aVat about 35,000 kilometers altitude.
p86
aVSatellites there remain in the same place above Earth as the Earth rotates,
p87
aVwhich enables things like communications or television broadcast, for example.
p88
aVSatellites in high orbits like these could remain there for centuries.
p89
aVAnd then there's the orbit coined "the graveyard,"
p90
aVthe ominous junk or disposal orbits,
p91
aVwhere some satellites are intentionally placed
p92
aVat the end of their life
p93
aVso that they're out of the way of common operational orbits.
