aa(lp104
VNow, because space debris and junk has become increasingly worrisome,
p105
aVthere have been some national and international efforts
p106
aVto develop technical standards
p107
aVto help us limit the generation of additional debris.
p108
aVSo for example, there are recommendations
p109
aVfor those low-Earth orbiting spacecraft
p110
aVto be made to deorbit in under 25 years,
p111
aVbut that's still a really long time,
p112
aVespecially if a satellite hasn't been working for years.
p113
aVThere's also mandates for those dead geostationary spacecraft
p114
aVto be moved into a graveyard orbit.
p115
aVBut neither of these guidelines is binding under international law,
p116
aVand the understanding is that they will be implemented through national mechanisms.
p117
aVThese guidelines are also not long-term,
p118
aVthey're not proactive,
p119
aVnor do they address the debris that's already up there.
p120
aVThey're only in place to limit the future creation of debris.
